# Standing Committee on Fisheries and Oceans (FOPO)

**Background:** New members have been appointed to the Standing Committee on Fisheries and Oceans (FOPO) which plays a decisive role in shaping Canada's Marine Protected Areas policy. Deep divisions exist between members advocating for full conservation measures and those pushing to exempt industrial activities like bottom trawling and open-net pen aquaculture from MPA restrictions. *\* Denotes active connections*  
---

## 1\. Chair \- Patrick Weiler (Liberal \- West Vancouver \- Sunshine Coast \- Sea to Sky Country, BC)\*

![Patrick Weiler][image1]

Patrick Weiler, born in 1986, is a trained environmental and natural resource management lawyer (J.D., UBC; B.A., McGill). His legal career focused on environmental and aboriginal law. His work included collaboration at the United Nations to improve the management of aquatic ecosystems. Elected in 2019 and re-elected in 2021 and 2025\. He has worked with First Nations, governments, and international organizations on aquatic ecosystem governance and sustainability. As an MP, he has become one of the strongest Liberal voices for ocean protection.

Weiler supported the creation of Canada's largest Marine Protected Area in 2024 (\~133,000 km¬≤ off BC's coast) and consistently backs the federal 30x30 target. He has advocated for science-based marine conservation that incorporates Indigenous governance. Environmental organizations such as the David Suzuki Foundation frequently consult him on MPA strategy. He is expected to strongly support the Great Bear Sea MPA network, provided it upholds consultation and long-term ecosystem integrity.

## Key Positions

- **MPAs:** Strong supporter of coastal MPAs; advocates for science-based protections, including no-trawl zones in sensitive habitats.  
- **Fish Farms:** Supports phasing out open-net pens in BC by 2025, citing risks to wild salmon. Backs Indigenous-led conservation.  
- **Licensing:** Supports reallocating salmon licenses to Indigenous fishers  
- **Coastline:** Riding in a B.C. coastal location.  
- **Conflicts/Notes:** Close ties to Pacific Salmon Foundation; criticizes DFO for slow action on aquaculture reform.

## Voting Record

- ‚úÖ **For** banning harmful fishing gear in MPAs (2023)  
- ‚ùå **Against** Conservative motions to delay B.C. fish farm closures (2022)

## Riding Information

## Public Statements & Media Analysis

Weiler, as FOPO Chair, projects an image of a moderate Liberal with environmentalist credentials (he's a former environmental lawyer). He has touted housing, climate adaptation, and Indigenous relations in local media. However, he has also publicly challenged his own party leadership. In late 2024 he argued that Prime Minister Trudeau "does not have the support of a significant amount of his caucus" and "should resign". These statements expose internal Liberal divisions and could be used to question his loyalty and consistency.

## Social Media & Digital Footprint

Weiler is active on Twitter and Instagram with mostly positive local content (community events, announcements). A notable digital posture is his endorsement of Mark Carney in the 2025 Liberal leadership race. Opponents might note his support for younger voter-friendly initiatives like lowering the voting age to 16, appealing to some but potentially seen as extreme by others. He generally avoids personal controversies online.

## Political & Policy Record

He was elected in 2019 and re-elected with growing margins. Policy-wise, Weiler has emphasized environmental protection: he defended carbon pricing and climate action in his riding. He sponsored water infrastructure and Indigenous partnership projects in BC. His committee work includes climate change and indigenous affairs, but FOPO as Chair is his primary role. He has also backed electoral reform (Bill C-210) and an immediate Gaza ceasefire, positions not universally popular.

## 2\. Vice Chair \- Mel Arnold (Conservative \- Kamloops \- Shuswap \- Central Rockies, BC)

![Mel Arnold][image2]

Mel Arnold is a senior Conservative MP with a background in wildlife and angling organizations. He is a longstanding critic of the federal 30x30 target and MPAs he sees as lacking consultation or economic planning. Between 1980's and 2015 was the owner of Twin Anchors Fishing Lodge (Salmon Arm, BC). As a director of the BC Wildlife Federation (2009 \- 2015\) lobbied for hunting/fishing access.

Arnold has directly criticized the Great Bear Sea MPA plan, citing testimony from BC fishers who felt betrayed by DFO's decisions. He argues for adaptive marine management rather than strict no-take zones and calls current MPA expansion politically motivated.

## Key Positions

- **MPAs:** Opposes "top-down" MPAs; argues they harm sport fishing and coastal economies. Pushed for exemptions in protected zones.  
- **Fish Farms:** Fierce defender of salmon farms; accuses Liberals of "destroying rural jobs." Rejects claims that farms harm wild salmon.  
- **Conflicts/Notes:** Receives strong support from BC aquaculture industry; has called DFO science "biased."

He also opposed the federal carbon tax in letters and public statements, drawing criticism from environmental advocates. These stances undermine his credibility on environmental issues, especially in a committee focused on ecosystems and MPAs.

## Social Media & Digital Footprint

Arnold maintains active Facebook and Instagram pages for his Conservative campaigns, promoting social conservative views. He has endorsed pro-life legislation (voting for a ban on sex-selective abortion) and supported anti-transgender "parental rights" rhetoric. This mixed record reflects a socially conservative brand.

## Political & Policy Record

Arnold votes reliably with the Conservative caucus. Notably he supported legislation to increase penalties on parents of transgender youth and has opposed many Liberal environmental initiatives. He has championed repealing climate policy and cutting funding for environmental programs, aligning with the party's resource industry ties.

## Affiliations & Relationships

An outspoken evangelical Christian, Arnold is closely aligned with right-wing interest groups. Campaign Life Coalition rates him highly on "pro-life" issues. He was a leader in forming Conservative Bible study groups on Parliament Hill and maintains ties to social conservative lobbyists.

## 9\. Member \- Robert J. Morrissey (Liberal \- Egmont, PEI)

![][image9]

Robert (Bobby) Morrissey has served as the Liberal MP for Egmont since 2015 and previously held provincial cabinet roles in Prince Edward Island. His work in Parliament has focused on Veterans Affairs, rural development, and agriculture, with less direct involvement in fisheries or marine conservation files.

Prior to entering politics in 1982, Morrissey was employed in the fishery. Since 2000, he was a consultant specializing in corporate/government relations, fisheries, labor market, and community development. He was also President of PFI Group, President of Global Food Technologies, and Director of Royal Star Investments.

He has generally followed the Liberal line on environmental and economic issues, supporting 30x30 targets and rural infrastructure investment. However, he has kept a low national profile and is seen as a stable, backbench supporter rather than a policy driver on FOPO.

## 10\. Member \- Clifford Small (Conservative ‚Äî Central Newfoundland, NL)

![Clifford Small][image10]

Before entering politics, he worked in the fishing industry as a harvester and in seafood processing. His background has influenced his focus on commercial fisheries and opposition to policies he views as restrictive to industry, such as marine protected areas (MPAs) and regulations on aquaculture. Small has publicly criticized federal environmental policies, including expanded MPAs and salmon farm closures in British Columbia, arguing they harm rural livelihoods without sufficient scientific justification.

As a member of the Standing Committee on Fisheries and Oceans (FOPO), he has advocated for open-net pen aquaculture and resisted catch restrictions tied to conservation goals. His positions align with the Conservative Party's emphasis on resource-sector economic growth over regulatory constraints. He has become a high-profile opponent of MPAs and marine conservation zones, describing them as government overreach threatening Atlantic livelihoods.

Small has opposed the proposed NMCA on Newfoundland's south coast, supports seal culls to protect fish stocks, and is closely aligned with aquaculture and fishery associations. He often casts conservationists as out-of-touch with the realities of working fishers.

## Key Positions

- **MPAs:** Argues MPAs kill rural jobs; demands exemptions for Newfoundland fisheries  
- **Fish Farms:** Champion of Atlantic aquaculture; calls B.C. phase-out "disastrous"  
- **Licensing:** Opposes redistributing crab quotas  
- **Conflicts/Notes:** Former fish plant owner; staunch industry ally
